{{Infobox scientist|name = George Barry Purdy |birth_date = 20 February 1944 |birth_place = [[San Francisco, California]], United States |death_date = 30 December 2017 |death_place = [[Cincinnati, Ohio]], United States |fields = [[Mathematics]] and [[computer science]] |workplaces = {{hlist|[[University of Cincinnati]]|[[Texas A&M University]]}} |alma_mater = [[University of Illinois]] |academic_advisors = [[Richard Rado]] |doctoral_advisor = {{hlist|[[Paul T. Bateman]]<ref name="mg">{{mathgenealogy|name=George Barry Purdy|id=3989}}</ref>|[[Paul Erdős]]}} |doctoral_students = |known_for = {{hlist|[[Discrete geometry]]|[[Number theory]]|[[Cryptography]]}} |footnotes = He has an [[Erdős number]] of one. }} '''George Barry Purdy''' (20 February 1944 – 30 December 2017)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://obittree.com/obituary/us/ohio/cincinnati/tp-white--sons-funeral-home/dr-george-purdy-phd/3389156/|title=Dr. George B. Purdy Phd Obituary - Cincinnati, OH {{!}} ObitTree™|website=obittree.com|language=en|access-date=2018-01-06}}</ref> was a [[mathematician]] and [[computer scientist]] who specialized in [[cryptography]], [[combinatorial geometry]] and [[number theory]]. Purdy received his Ph.D. from the [[University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign]] in 1972, officially under the supervision of [[Paul T. Bateman]],<ref name="mg"/> but his de facto adviser was [[Paul Erdős]].{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} He was on the faculty in the mathematics department at [[Texas A&M University]] for 11 years, and was appointed the Geier Professor of computer science at the [[University of Cincinnati]] in 1986.
Purdy had [[Erdős number]] one and coauthored many papers with Paul Erdős, who regarded him as his own student.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} He is the "P" in [[G.W. Peck]], a pseudonym for the group of mathematicians that also included [[Ronald Graham]], [[Douglas West (mathematician)|Douglas West]], [[Paul Erdős]], [[Fan Chung]], and [[Daniel Kleitman]].<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1016/S0012-365X(02)00595-2|last=Peck|first=G. W.|year=2002|title=Kleitman and combinatorics: a celebration|journal=Discrete Mathematics|publisher=Elsevier |volume=257|issue=2–3|pages=193–224|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science?_ob=ArticleURL&_udi=B6V00-46TBX9G-3&_user=10&_rdoc=1&_fmt=&_orig=search&_sort=d&_docanchor=&view=c&_acct=C000050221&_version=1&_urlVersion=0&_userid=10&md5=404a0535417d056b4a18327185af64a0}}</ref>
==Purdy polynomial== In 1971, Purdy was asked by [[Lawrence Roberts (scientist)|Larry Roberts]], the head of [[DARPA]], to develop a secure [[hash function]] to protect passwords on [[ARPANET]]. Purdy developed the so-called '''Purdy polynomial''', which was a polynomial of degree 2<sup>24</sup> + 17 computed modulo the 64-bit [[prime number|prime]] ''p'' = 2<sup>64</sup> - 59. The terms of the polynomial could be computed using [[modular exponentiation]]. DARPA was satisfied with the hash function, and also allowed Purdy to publish it in [[Communications of the ACM]]. It was well received around the world, and [[Digital Equipment Corporation|DEC]] eventually used it in their [[OpenVMS]] operating system. A DEC report said they chose it because it was very secure, and also because the existing standard [[Data Encryption Standard|DES]] could not be exported, which meant that an alternative was needed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://passwordresearch.com/papers/paper73.html |title=Research Paper - A High Security Log-In Procedure |publisher=Passwordresearch.com |accessdate=2013-11-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=361089 |title=A high security log-in procedure |doi=10.1145/361082.361089 |publisher=Dl.acm.org |accessdate=2013-11-16}}</ref> OpenVMS<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metacpan.org/module/Authen::Passphrase::VMSPurdy#DESCRIPTION|title=Authen::Passphrase::VMSPurdy – passphrases with the VMS Purdy polynomial system|work=[[CPAN]]|accessdate=2009-09-18}}</ref> uses a 64-bit version, based on a 64-bit prime, the same size as the one in the paper.
==Purdy's conjecture==
While at Texas A&M, Purdy made an empirical observation about distances between points on two lines. Suppose that ''n'' points are to be chosen on line ''L'' and another ''n'' points on line ''M''. If ''L'' and ''M'' are [[perpendicular]] or [[parallel (geometry)|parallel]], then the points can be chosen so that the number of distinct distances determined is bounded by a constant multiply of ''n'', but otherwise the number is much larger. Erdős was very struck by this conjecture and told it to many others, and it was published in a book of unsolved problems by [[William Moser]] in 1981.<ref>L. Moser and J. Pach, Research problems in discrete geometry, McGill University, Montreal, 1981</ref> It came to the attention of [[György Elekes]], who eventually proved the conjecture as the first application of new tools from [[algebraic geometry]] that he was developing.<ref>''A Combinatorial Problem on Polynomials and Rational Functions'', György Elekes, Lajos Rónyai, Journal of Combinatorial Theory, Series A, Volume 89, Issue 1, January 2000, Pages 1–20</ref> After Elekes's untimely death, [[Micha Sharir]] collected Elekes's notes and published an organized presentation of these algebraic methods, including work of his own. This, in turn, enabled [[Nets Katz|Katz]] and [[Larry Guth|Guth]] to solve the [[Erdős distinct distances problem]], a 1946 problem of Erdős. Work continues on improvements in Purdy's conjecture.<ref>''Distinct distances on two lines'', Micha Sharir, Adam Sheffer, [[József Solymosi]], June 4, 2013, https://arxiv.org/pdf/1302.3081.pdf</ref>
==Awards== In 2015, Purdy was awarded the [[Joseph Desch#The IEEE Joe Desch Innovation Award|IEEE Joseph Desch Award for Innovation]] for his work on the [[ARPANET|Arpa Network]] and the Purdy Polynomial.
